 engaged and how this fed over into the realm of politics; and the fashion for tourism at home and abroad. It also asks how elite women used polite social spaces and practices to extend their mental horizons and to form a sense of belonging to a public at a time when Scotland was among the most intellectually vibrant societies in Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aElite (Social sciences)zScotlandxHistoryy18th century. 0aWomenzScotlandxSocial conditionsy18th century. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aModern History. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 18th Century.2bisacsh  aScotland.  aeducation.  aeighteenth century.  aelite women.  apolite society.  areading practices.  asociability.  atourism.  aurban settings.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615850640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846158506423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846158506/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles